children. In order to remedy this situation, breast feeding has gained the 
importance of a national program. Other unresolved issues include the high 
neonatal mortality rate, and the increasing maternal mortality rate (from 76.4 
per 100,000 live births in 1991 to 84.2 per 100,000 currently). There has been a 
functioning family planning service and a system of social patronage since 1989. 
In the latter system, a social worker takes charge of families at risk. One 
worker on average attends 30 families. The International Planned Parenthood 
Federation has financed 689 social patronage workers over the past year. 
International organizations have supported the supply of contraceptives through 
humanitarian aid. Because of this, the number of women accepting family planning 
is rising and the fertility rate is decreasing (from 28.2 per 1000 in 1991 to 
26.9 in 1993).

