570. Entre Nous Cph Den. 1999 Winter;(45):13-4.

Highlight on women's health -- Ukraine.

Savblom C.

PIP: The reference document, "Highlight on Women's Health", shows a decline in 
women's health over the last 4 years in the Republic of Ukraine. This is 
evidenced by the fact that the life expectancy at birth for women declined to 
72.8 in 1997. Factors contributing to this decrease include cardiovascular 
diseases, cancer, accidents, poisoning and trauma. In addition, total fertility 
rate declined to 1.3 in 1996 from 1.7 in 1994, citing abortion as the main form 
of birth control. Maternal mortality among the regions ranged from 12 to 70 per 
100,000 live births. However, the overall maternal mortality rate slightly 
decreased and was 30.4 per 100,000 live births in 1996, with abortion being the 
leading cause for maternal deaths. Moreover, the 1996 morbidity rate from 
syphilis among girls aged 16-18 years was 63.3/100,000; from gonorrhea, 
73.3/100,000. Prevalence of AIDS rose more than 7 times between December 1994 
and 1996. A total of 5444 people in the Ukraine were officially infected with 
HIV; 23% of these were women.

